—and, thus, how politics exists in us individually, long before it plays a role in the establishment of societies and institutions. Through these figurations of power, Schabert argues, we learn how to institute our own government within the political forces that already surround us—to create our own world within the one into which we have been born. In a stunning vision of human agency, this book ultimately sketches a political cosmos in which we are all builders, in which we can be at once political and free.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCivilization. 0aPolitical sciencexAnthropological aspects. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 70(DE-601)1056534460(DE-588)4136977-4aDas @Politische2gnd 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ahuman, history, historical, academic, scholarly, politics, political, poli sci, philosophy, philosophical, theory, theoretical, society, social studies, birth, mythical, mythology, religious, religion, faith, belief, global, international, america, europe, middle east, eastern, western, china, asia, transcultural, culture, government, power.1 aIbáñez-Noé, Javier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022603805640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226185156423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226185156/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles